00:00:51.460 --> 00:00:55.715
These are a set of APIs we've
had available for a while, but

00:00:55.715 --> 00:00:57.930
I'm not sure people have taken
advantage of them to the

00:00:57.930 --> 00:00:59.300
extent that they should have.

00:00:59.300 --> 00:01:03.590
And so Wolff has come to the
rescue on behalf of all you

00:01:03.590 --> 00:01:04.290
developers.

00:01:04.290 --> 00:01:06.120
And he's made life
easier for you.

00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:07.850
So we're going to have
him talk about it.

00:01:07.850 --> 00:01:08.320
WOLFF DOBSON: All right.

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:10.820
So the admin tools--

00:01:10.820 --> 00:01:12.470
here's this link to the
docs if you want to

00:01:12.470 --> 00:01:13.850
check them out yourself.

00:01:13.850 --> 00:01:17.980
Basically, they are a bunch of
REST calls that allow you to

00:01:17.980 --> 00:01:22.660
do certain management tasks,
like reset achievements, hide

00:01:22.660 --> 00:01:27.550
players on high score lists,
un-unlock achievements--

00:01:27.550 --> 00:01:28.490
that sort of thing.

00:01:28.490 --> 00:01:29.620
TODD KERPELMAN: Reset
your score--

00:01:29.620 --> 00:01:30.170
WOLFF DOBSON: You've got it.

00:01:30.170 --> 00:01:31.260
TODD KERPELMAN: --while
youre in testing.

00:01:31.260 --> 00:01:33.980
WOLFF DOBSON: And I bet when I
say that, you're thinking, I

00:01:33.980 --> 00:01:36.330
don't want to make all these
REST calls myself.

00:01:36.330 --> 00:01:38.640
I wish somebody had actually
written that for me.

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:41.280
And the answer is
somebody has.

00:01:41.280 --> 00:01:42.170
And that person is me.

00:01:42.170 --> 00:01:45.360
So let's take a look.

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:47.830
So here's the first
of three tools.

00:01:47.830 --> 00:01:49.890
This is the Play Games
Score-o-matic.

00:01:49.890 --> 00:01:52.190
And what this allows you
to do is set and

00:01:52.190 --> 00:01:54.080
reset leaderboard scores.

00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:58.800
So this is the leaderboard from
Firewall Defense, Bruno's

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:00.010
excellent game.

00:02:00.010 --> 00:02:03.220
And I can get the scores
that I've submitted.

00:02:03.220 --> 00:02:05.920
Now, I haven't submitted any
scores, so let's make myself

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:07.795
score a whole bunch of scores.

00:02:07.795 --> 00:02:10.380
I'm going to score
10,000 points.

00:02:10.380 --> 00:02:11.135
And it says, great.

00:02:11.135 --> 00:02:12.770
Your score is submitted.

00:02:12.770 --> 00:02:15.820
And then if I call to
get my scores, I've

00:02:15.820 --> 00:02:16.790
scored 10,000 points.

00:02:16.790 --> 00:02:21.080
And I'm first in my social
group of two.

00:02:21.080 --> 00:02:21.755
TODD KERPELMAN: How come you're

00:02:21.755 --> 00:02:24.300
listed three times there?

00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:27.650
WOLFF DOBSON: That's for
all-time high score, weekly

00:02:27.650 --> 00:02:29.780
high score, and daily
high score.

00:02:29.780 --> 00:02:30.480
TODD KERPELMAN: OK.

00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:33.100
WOLFF DOBSON: And I can reset
all the scores with one click

00:02:33.100 --> 00:02:33.910
of a button.

00:02:33.910 --> 00:02:34.730
I'm reset--

00:02:34.730 --> 00:02:35.500
boink.

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:37.985
And when I get my scores again,
I've disappeared.

00:02:37.985 --> 00:02:38.330
TODD KERPELMAN: Ah.

00:02:38.330 --> 00:02:41.120
So this would be very
useful if, say,

00:02:41.120 --> 00:02:42.320
we're testing our game.

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:45.700
Our scoreboard is full of
testers that have either found

00:02:45.700 --> 00:02:48.195
bugs to get ridiculously
high scores, and

00:02:48.195 --> 00:02:48.770
we're like, oh man.

00:02:48.770 --> 00:02:50.790
We've got to clear this
out before we launch.

00:02:50.790 --> 00:02:51.405
WOLFF DOBSON: Yeah.

00:02:51.405 --> 00:02:55.390
Or you have a system that does
something special when you get

00:02:55.390 --> 00:02:57.100
daily high scores or something
like that.

00:02:57.100 --> 00:02:58.770
You want to be able to set
that off again and again.

00:02:58.770 --> 00:03:00.250
So this is a way for
you to reset that.

00:03:00.250 --> 00:03:01.740
You can only reset
your high score.

00:03:01.740 --> 00:03:03.240
You can't reset everybody's
high score.

00:03:03.240 --> 00:03:03.840
TODD KERPELMAN: OK.

00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:05.050
That's probably important
to know.

00:03:05.050 --> 00:03:05.640
WOLFF DOBSON: OK.

00:03:05.640 --> 00:03:07.600
Next up is the Reset-o-matic.

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:10.220
The Reset-o-matic is the
same thing, except for

00:03:10.220 --> 00:03:10.880
achievements.

00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:12.090
So here, we have a list of

00:03:12.090 --> 00:03:16.180
achievements in Firewall Defense.

00:03:16.180 --> 00:03:18.510
I'm going to take this
cadet thing, and I'm

00:03:18.510 --> 00:03:19.820
going to unlock it.

00:03:19.820 --> 00:03:20.520
Da-ding--

00:03:20.520 --> 00:03:21.560
achievement unlocked.

00:03:21.560 --> 00:03:23.270
And when I refresh this--

00:03:23.270 --> 00:03:25.010
phoomph--

00:03:25.010 --> 00:03:27.330
you can see it is
now unlocked.

00:03:27.330 --> 00:03:28.750
Hooray.

00:03:28.750 --> 00:03:30.360
I could also, if it were an
incremental achievement,

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:31.320
increment it.

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:33.240
And I can also just say,
nah, I didn't win

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:34.540
that on second thought.

00:03:34.540 --> 00:03:40.360
And when I refresh,
it is now still

00:03:40.360 --> 00:03:42.610
revealed rather than unlocked.

00:03:42.610 --> 00:03:44.760
TODD KERPELMAN: Revealed
here meaning that--

00:03:44.760 --> 00:03:46.590
I always find our achievement
states confusing.

00:03:46.590 --> 00:03:49.150
Revealed means that you know
the achievement is, but you

00:03:49.150 --> 00:03:49.990
haven't earned it yet--

00:03:49.990 --> 00:03:50.300
WOLFF DOBSON: Right.

00:03:50.300 --> 00:03:51.253
TODD KERPELMAN: --as
opposed to hidden.

00:03:51.253 --> 00:03:53.920
WOLFF DOBSON: Or unlocked, which
means you've actually--

00:03:53.920 --> 00:03:54.740
achievement unlocked.

00:03:54.740 --> 00:03:55.480
TODD KERPELMAN: Yes.

00:03:55.480 --> 00:03:58.450
And so this is incredibly
useful if, again, we're

00:03:58.450 --> 00:04:00.960
testing achievements before
our game goes out.

00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:04.210
And we want to practice earning
an achievement, we

00:04:04.210 --> 00:04:05.810
want to test that over
and over again.

00:04:05.810 --> 00:04:08.150
You don't have to create
500 test accounts.

00:04:08.150 --> 00:04:09.080
We just--

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:10.470
WOLFF DOBSON: No, you wouldn't
want to do that.

00:04:10.470 --> 00:04:11.620
TODD KERPELMAN: Yeah-- reset
this achievement.

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:12.840
WOLFF DOBSON: You'd be sad.

00:04:12.840 --> 00:04:13.550
OK.

00:04:13.550 --> 00:04:16.600
So then lastly, we have
the Hide-o-matic.

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:18.610
And the Hide-o-matic is the one
that you're really going

00:04:18.610 --> 00:04:21.250
to use, possibly, from week
to week when you're

00:04:21.250 --> 00:04:23.600
developing your game.

00:04:23.600 --> 00:04:29.370
So this is the main high score
list for Firewall Defense.

00:04:29.370 --> 00:04:31.525
And you might look through here,
and you say, well, all

00:04:31.525 --> 00:04:33.130
these guys got their scores
legitimately.

00:04:33.130 --> 00:04:37.060
But when I say I look through
here, I see Bruno.

00:04:37.060 --> 00:04:39.320
And Bruno is a developer
of the game.

00:04:39.320 --> 00:04:42.125
It's clear he didn't score those
6,000 points by himself.

00:04:42.125 --> 00:04:42.970
TODD KERPELMAN: No way.

00:04:42.970 --> 00:04:44.500
WOLFF DOBSON: So I'm going
to go here, and I'm

00:04:44.500 --> 00:04:46.140
going to say, be gone.

00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:47.550
I'm going to hide you forever.

00:04:47.550 --> 00:04:49.440
And so this player's
now hidden.

00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:52.730
And if I refresh the high
scores and I page to the

00:04:52.730 --> 00:04:55.460
second page, you can
see there's no

00:04:55.460 --> 00:04:58.020
Bruno there any longer.

00:04:58.020 --> 00:04:59.580
That's totally cool.

00:04:59.580 --> 00:05:02.280
And if I decide to have mercy on
Bruno and bring him back, I

00:05:02.280 --> 00:05:04.950
can click Unhide and
he's unhidden.

00:05:04.950 --> 00:05:08.700
It'll take 12 hours for
Bruno to reappear.

00:05:08.700 --> 00:05:11.370
It's a low priority job, so it's
going to come back when

00:05:11.370 --> 00:05:12.290
it's going to come back.

00:05:12.290 --> 00:05:14.400
TODD KERPELMAN: Now, when you
hide this player, are they

00:05:14.400 --> 00:05:16.540
hidden from all leaderboards,
or just this particularly

00:05:16.540 --> 00:05:17.490
leaderboard?

00:05:17.490 --> 00:05:20.420
WOLFF DOBSON: No, they are
hidden from all leaderboards.

00:05:20.420 --> 00:05:22.950
TODD KERPELMAN: OK.

00:05:22.950 --> 00:05:23.590
WOLFF DOBSON: All right.

00:05:23.590 --> 00:05:25.430
Well, those are the
management tools.

00:05:25.430 --> 00:05:26.640
These are all open source.

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:28.640
You can get them yourself
from GitHub

00:05:28.640 --> 00:05:30.485
from our regular samples.

00:05:30.485 --> 00:05:32.060
TODD KERPELMAN: And I guess it's
probably worth noticing,

00:05:32.060 --> 00:05:34.600
compared to most of our sample
apps that are like, hey,

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:37.870
here's a sample that you can see
how it works, but then you

00:05:37.870 --> 00:05:41.560
need to go and make your own
game and copy and paste bits

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:43.470
here and there from our samples,
this is really

00:05:43.470 --> 00:05:46.790
intended for people to
essentially use as an entire

00:05:46.790 --> 00:05:47.200
application.

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:48.750
You download this thing.

00:05:48.750 --> 00:05:49.520
They run it.

00:05:49.520 --> 00:05:49.840
WOLFF DOBSON: Yeah.

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:51.690
TODD KERPELMAN: And in fact, I
guess, probably, you can walk

00:05:51.690 --> 00:05:52.810
us through the setup steps.

00:05:52.810 --> 00:05:55.650
But it really is hey, this is
the code that you should be

00:05:55.650 --> 00:05:57.280
using on your own.

00:05:57.280 --> 00:05:59.860
WOLFF DOBSON: And because it's
an API, you can expand it

00:05:59.860 --> 00:06:00.400
anyway you want.

00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:01.260
TODD KERPELMAN: Yeah.

00:06:01.260 --> 00:06:01.540
WOLFF DOBSON: All right.

00:06:01.540 --> 00:06:04.202
Well, let's take a look at how
we're going to set this up.

00:06:04.202 --> 00:06:07.345
For you to use these tools,
you're going to need to host

00:06:07.345 --> 00:06:08.100
them someplace.

00:06:08.100 --> 00:06:09.980
They're just a couple
of HTML pages and

00:06:09.980 --> 00:06:11.240
some JavaScript pages.

00:06:11.240 --> 00:06:12.690
You'll need to put
them someplace.

00:06:12.690 --> 00:06:15.410
Localhost even works
for testing.

00:06:15.410 --> 00:06:16.660
You're going to need
to link a web

00:06:16.660 --> 00:06:17.840
application in the console.

00:06:17.840 --> 00:06:21.820
And you're going to need to go
into these JavaScript and the

00:06:21.820 --> 00:06:24.440
HTML files and replace
couple of constants--

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:27.770
in this case, CLIENT_ID,
APP_ID, and in the

00:06:27.770 --> 00:06:30.540
Hide-o-matic, you need
the leaderboard.

00:06:30.540 --> 00:06:35.630
So even if you don't have a
web version of your game--

00:06:35.630 --> 00:06:36.820
TODD KERPELMAN: --which probably
applies to a lot of

00:06:36.820 --> 00:06:37.260
our mobile developers.

00:06:37.260 --> 00:06:38.510
WOLFF DOBSON: Yeah, exactly--
a lot of your developers.

00:06:41.060 --> 00:06:43.530
You're going to need to link
a web application anyway.

00:06:43.530 --> 00:06:47.090
And this web application
is actually your game.

00:06:47.090 --> 00:06:49.190
So you should be careful with
those credentials like you

00:06:49.190 --> 00:06:50.050
would normally.

00:06:50.050 --> 00:06:52.130
TODD KERPELMAN: So sorry, just
to clarify, I'm not going to

00:06:52.130 --> 00:06:55.630
create a new application that's
my admin for my Angry

00:06:55.630 --> 00:06:56.130
Fruit game.

00:06:56.130 --> 00:06:58.310
I'm actually going to go into
my Angry Fruit game and I'm

00:06:58.310 --> 00:07:00.490
going to link to
a new web-based

00:07:00.490 --> 00:07:01.640
client ID for this game.

00:07:01.640 --> 00:07:03.650
WOLFF DOBSON: Yeah, it's
a web version of

00:07:03.650 --> 00:07:05.010
your Angry Fruit game.

00:07:05.010 --> 00:07:05.970
TODD KERPELMAN: OK.

00:07:05.970 --> 00:07:07.396
WOLFF DOBSON: And you're going
to fill out where you want it

00:07:07.396 --> 00:07:10.190
to point to, and you're going
to create a client ID.

00:07:10.190 --> 00:07:12.560
And when you create the client
ID for the web console, you

00:07:12.560 --> 00:07:14.840
need to set your JavaScript
origins to wherever you're

00:07:14.840 --> 00:07:16.680
hosting these pages.

00:07:16.680 --> 00:07:19.850
In this case, I have it on
localhost, but you could also

00:07:19.850 --> 00:07:22.280
host it just on a server inside
your firewall, or even

00:07:22.280 --> 00:07:23.830
public, although you'd
have to be pretty

00:07:23.830 --> 00:07:25.080
careful with that URL.

00:07:27.860 --> 00:07:31.130
It is worth noting that
this is, in fact, a

00:07:31.130 --> 00:07:31.990
version of your game.

00:07:31.990 --> 00:07:34.080
It's just a version of your game
with your game missing

00:07:34.080 --> 00:07:36.570
and just the leaderboards and
the scoreboard stuff in there.

00:07:36.570 --> 00:07:41.400
And so if you have a JavaScript
origin set to

00:07:41.400 --> 00:07:43.780
localhost, it means
that anybody else

00:07:43.780 --> 00:07:44.810
can download this.

00:07:44.810 --> 00:07:46.360
And they can go to the web
version of your game and they

00:07:46.360 --> 00:07:49.690
can pull out the client ID and
the app ID and paste those in

00:07:49.690 --> 00:07:52.180
your things and unlock all
the achievements and give

00:07:52.180 --> 00:07:53.580
themselves arbitrary score.

00:07:53.580 --> 00:07:57.940
They won't be able to do the
management tasks, because you

00:07:57.940 --> 00:08:01.270
have to be an owner or
on the tester list

00:08:01.270 --> 00:08:02.260
to use those things.

00:08:02.260 --> 00:08:05.050
But they will be able to,
obviously, just set their

00:08:05.050 --> 00:08:06.020
scores arbitrarily.

00:08:06.020 --> 00:08:08.130
And you want to be careful
with that.

00:08:08.130 --> 00:08:11.560
So I would advise, if your game
is launched, you probably

00:08:11.560 --> 00:08:13.760
want to set your JavaScript
origin to something besides

00:08:13.760 --> 00:08:14.740
localhost--

00:08:14.740 --> 00:08:19.270
probably an internal server
that's inside your firewall.

00:08:19.270 --> 00:08:19.760
OK.

