00:12:19.210 --> 00:12:20.510
JAVIER SNIDER: Yes.

00:12:20.510 --> 00:12:21.890
TODD KERPELMAN: I've got
this whole seat here.

00:12:21.890 --> 00:12:25.030
I think I really only need the
edge, because we're about to

00:12:25.030 --> 00:12:26.220
reveal it right now.

00:12:26.220 --> 00:12:26.900
JAVIER SNIDER: OK.

00:12:26.900 --> 00:12:27.730
TODD KERPELMAN: Hey,
check that out.

00:12:27.730 --> 00:12:28.420
JAVIER SNIDER: OK.

00:12:28.420 --> 00:12:29.680
TODD KERPELMAN: So what
are we looking at?

00:12:29.680 --> 00:12:30.130
JAVIER SNIDER: What is this?

00:12:30.130 --> 00:12:30.440
TODD KERPELMAN: What is it?

00:12:30.440 --> 00:12:30.720
JAVIER SNIDER: OK.

00:12:30.720 --> 00:12:35.350
Well, this is an improvement
in the unreliable latency

00:12:35.350 --> 00:12:39.450
between peers and real-time
multiplayer games.

00:12:39.450 --> 00:12:39.840
TODD KERPELMAN: OK.

00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:44.930
So I know we launched
multiplayer matchmaking at

00:12:44.930 --> 00:12:47.130
Google I/O a few months ago.

00:12:47.130 --> 00:12:50.680
Since then, we've been
integrating and improving.

00:12:50.680 --> 00:12:54.460
One of those areas has
been match quality.

00:12:54.460 --> 00:12:55.600
JAVIER SNIDER: Yeah,
match quality.

00:12:55.600 --> 00:12:56.430
So what is this?

00:12:56.430 --> 00:13:01.840
This is a factor that we are
always trying to improve in

00:13:01.840 --> 00:13:07.860
our matchmaking system so the
players can have a better

00:13:07.860 --> 00:13:12.860
experience in the matches
that we create.

00:13:12.860 --> 00:13:15.010
TODD KERPELMAN: It looks like a
couple weeks ago, this graph

00:13:15.010 --> 00:13:16.870
took a nice little dip.

00:13:16.870 --> 00:13:17.440
JAVIER SNIDER: Yes.

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:18.020
TODD KERPELMAN: What
happened here?

00:13:18.020 --> 00:13:19.430
JAVIER SNIDER: So
what is this?

00:13:19.430 --> 00:13:29.850
We started considering the broad
geographic place of our

00:13:29.850 --> 00:13:35.170
players to estimate the latency
that they are going to

00:13:35.170 --> 00:13:40.360
have when we form the match.

00:13:40.360 --> 00:13:40.760
TODD KERPELMAN: Gotcha.

00:13:40.760 --> 00:13:43.550
So you basically now prefer--

00:13:43.550 --> 00:13:46.760
if I'm somewhere in, say,
Seattle, you're saying, hey,

00:13:46.760 --> 00:13:49.070
we're going to try and match you
with other people in the

00:13:49.070 --> 00:13:52.000
Pacific Northwest area, because
chances are you'll

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:55.200
have better latency than if we
match you with somebody in--

00:13:55.200 --> 00:13:55.470
JAVIER SNIDER: Exactly.

00:13:55.470 --> 00:14:00.305
So this is something tricky,
because we don't know the

00:14:00.305 --> 00:14:05.015
right latency after the match is
formed, and at that point,

00:14:05.015 --> 00:14:08.010
it's too late to choose
a different player.

00:14:08.010 --> 00:14:08.980
TODD KERPELMAN: You can't
kick someone out

00:14:08.980 --> 00:14:09.810
for having low latency.

00:14:09.810 --> 00:14:11.090
JAVIER SNIDER: No,
of course not.

00:14:11.090 --> 00:14:15.340
So what we have to do is to
collect data for all the

00:14:15.340 --> 00:14:17.850
matches between all the regions
around the world.

00:14:17.850 --> 00:14:23.340
And that data, we estimate
what is likely to be the

00:14:23.340 --> 00:14:27.220
latency between two players
in different regions.

00:14:27.220 --> 00:14:27.750
TODD KERPELMAN: Ah.

00:14:27.750 --> 00:14:29.570
So it doesn't necessarily have
to be in the same region.

00:14:29.570 --> 00:14:32.280
If we know that, for some
reason, City A and City B have

00:14:32.280 --> 00:14:34.700
a really good internet
connection between them--

00:14:34.700 --> 00:14:35.390
JAVIER SNIDER: Yes, exactly.

00:14:35.390 --> 00:14:36.660
TODD KERPELMAN: --your system
would say, oh, it's OK to

00:14:36.660 --> 00:14:37.350
match up these two.

00:14:37.350 --> 00:14:39.840
JAVIER SNIDER: Yes, exactly.

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:42.020
So essentially, we do that.

00:14:42.020 --> 00:14:47.330
And with this feature, we get
better quality in the matches.

00:14:47.330 --> 00:14:52.040
As you can see the graph, we've
had almost 15% or 20%

00:14:52.040 --> 00:14:52.405
improvement.

00:14:52.405 --> 00:14:53.600
TODD KERPELMAN: That
looks nice.

00:14:53.600 --> 00:14:54.160
JAVIER SNIDER: Yeah.

00:14:54.160 --> 00:14:56.590
TODD KERPELMAN: So were there
any trade offs involved in

00:14:56.590 --> 00:14:57.510
having to do this?

00:14:57.510 --> 00:14:57.590
JAVIER SNIDER: Yes.

00:14:57.590 --> 00:14:58.880
You always have those.

00:14:58.880 --> 00:15:05.830
So if we have a match or if when
we are forming a match we

00:15:05.830 --> 00:15:10.220
seen that this match is not
really a good quality or the

00:15:10.220 --> 00:15:16.700
latency is likely to be not so
good, but we don't have other

00:15:16.700 --> 00:15:20.790
players, probably we have to
wait a little longer to

00:15:20.790 --> 00:15:27.110
combine the matches in order
to wait for new players to

00:15:27.110 --> 00:15:33.230
arrive and see if they have
better quality or better

00:15:33.230 --> 00:15:35.580
expected latency between them.

00:15:35.580 --> 00:15:41.580
So this is the trade off, so
maybe we need the players to

00:15:41.580 --> 00:15:44.770
wait a little longer before
we find the matches.

00:15:44.770 --> 00:15:45.110
TODD KERPELMAN: Gotcha.

00:15:45.110 --> 00:15:48.000
So what you're saying is for
instance, I might be ready to

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:52.500
play and the only other player
available right now is in

00:15:52.500 --> 00:15:54.810
Australia or somewhere
where it's far away,

00:15:54.810 --> 00:15:57.340
probably longer latency.

00:15:57.340 --> 00:15:59.190
The system's going to say, we're
not going to match you

00:15:59.190 --> 00:16:00.770
up with that guy.

00:16:00.770 --> 00:16:02.610
We're going to look for somebody
else with a better

00:16:02.610 --> 00:16:03.430
connection.

00:16:03.430 --> 00:16:06.380
And so it might take me longer
to get into a match because

00:16:06.380 --> 00:16:07.910
I'm not going to play this
guy in Australia.

00:16:07.910 --> 00:16:08.460
JAVIER SNIDER: Yes.

00:16:08.460 --> 00:16:12.890
But of course, we don't want our
players to wait too much.

00:16:12.890 --> 00:16:18.500
So what we also estimate is the
waiting time to another

00:16:18.500 --> 00:16:22.260
player to appear for this
particular game.

00:16:22.260 --> 00:16:26.960
And if we think that it's going
to be too long, we don't

00:16:26.960 --> 00:16:30.660
wait, and combine the
players right away.

00:16:30.660 --> 00:16:34.440
TODD KERPELMAN: So you change
the criteria a little bit

00:16:34.440 --> 00:16:37.330
based on how popular the game
is, how many players are

00:16:37.330 --> 00:16:39.380
playing multiplayer
at that time?

00:16:39.380 --> 00:16:40.420
JAVIER SNIDER: Yeah, exactly.

00:16:40.420 --> 00:16:44.300
And this is something that
is dynamically adjusted.

00:16:44.300 --> 00:16:49.260
So for each application, each
variant, and each moment, we

00:16:49.260 --> 00:16:53.530
calculate all these variables
and decide if wait is a good

00:16:53.530 --> 00:16:54.770
idea or not.

00:16:54.770 --> 00:17:00.010
So we prioritize these two
things to have a good quality,

00:17:00.010 --> 00:17:05.450
but also not to wait too much
that the player drops the

00:17:05.450 --> 00:17:07.140
match or whatever.

00:17:07.140 --> 00:17:08.589
TODD KERPELMAN: So for instance,
in a very popular

00:17:08.589 --> 00:17:12.480
game, you could afford to reject
players that are too

00:17:12.480 --> 00:17:15.700
far away, might not have a good
connection, because we

00:17:15.700 --> 00:17:18.119
know that there's constantly new
people coming in and that

00:17:18.119 --> 00:17:19.410
I won't have to wait
too much longer to

00:17:19.410 --> 00:17:21.030
find a matching player.

00:17:21.030 --> 00:17:24.869
Whereas a game where it's just
been released or it's not very

00:17:24.869 --> 00:17:28.600
popular, no one's playing
multiplayer, even if some

00:17:28.600 --> 00:17:31.350
connection isn't optimal, the
system will say, we're going

00:17:31.350 --> 00:17:33.300
to try and match you with them
anyway, because at least it's

00:17:33.300 --> 00:17:35.670
better to have some game
than no game at all.

00:17:35.670 --> 00:17:36.800
JAVIER SNIDER: Yeah, exactly.

00:17:36.800 --> 00:17:37.670
That's the idea.

00:17:37.670 --> 00:17:39.865
And by the way, we don't
reject players.

00:17:39.865 --> 00:17:40.140
TODD KERPELMAN: Sorry.

00:17:40.140 --> 00:17:42.550
JAVIER SNIDER: We just
choose to combine

00:17:42.550 --> 00:17:43.640
them with other players.

00:17:43.640 --> 00:17:45.480
TODD KERPELMAN: You're right.

00:17:45.480 --> 00:17:47.210
I should pick better language.

00:17:47.210 --> 00:17:48.740
We love all of our players.

00:17:48.740 --> 00:17:49.480
We just--

00:17:49.480 --> 00:17:49.780
JAVIER SNIDER: Yeah.

00:17:49.780 --> 00:17:50.150
TODD KERPELMAN: OK.

00:17:50.150 --> 00:17:51.160
JAVIER SNIDER: OK.

00:17:51.160 --> 00:17:54.260
So this is it.

00:17:54.260 --> 00:17:57.160
TODD KERPELMAN: That's
very cool.

00:17:57.160 --> 00:17:59.770
So basically, our players should
be noticing a better

00:17:59.770 --> 00:18:01.250
multiplayer experience.

00:18:01.250 --> 00:18:02.280
JAVIER SNIDER: Yeah,
that's the idea.

00:18:02.280 --> 00:18:02.560
TODD KERPELMAN: Yeah.

00:18:02.560 --> 00:18:08.780
And over time, as you adjust
these matching systems, and I

00:18:08.780 --> 00:18:11.770
guess as more people start
playing multiplayer, they'll

00:18:11.770 --> 00:18:13.370
start to see improvements,
as well.

00:18:13.370 --> 00:18:14.620
JAVIER SNIDER: Yes.

00:18:16.840 --> 00:18:22.500
So another thing that maybe in
the future happens is if a

00:18:22.500 --> 00:18:28.900
player or developers want to
improve based on the skills of

00:18:28.900 --> 00:18:33.820
the players, we can do
some similar stuff.

00:18:33.820 --> 00:18:35.100
TODD KERPELMAN: I've seen
requests for that in the

00:18:35.100 --> 00:18:36.170
public database--

00:18:36.170 --> 00:18:39.250
hey, I want to match advanced
players with advanced players

00:18:39.250 --> 00:18:40.830
or people of the same
difficulty level.

00:18:40.830 --> 00:18:43.290
But I guess you do have a good
point where there's a trade

00:18:43.290 --> 00:18:47.260
off there, where if we start
not matching people with

00:18:47.260 --> 00:18:50.030
potential opponents just because
maybe they're not the

00:18:50.030 --> 00:18:52.790
same skill level, the wait
time is going to go up.

00:18:52.790 --> 00:18:58.150
And depending on how picky we
get, the more factors we have

00:18:58.150 --> 00:19:00.330
to wait until we get a perfect
match, the longer the wait

00:19:00.330 --> 00:19:01.210
time could be.

00:19:01.210 --> 00:19:02.000
JAVIER SNIDER: Yes.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:06.290
But of course, we have to
consider all these features or

00:19:06.290 --> 00:19:12.640
these parameters when we try to
